The crash you’re seeing (Minified React error #31) is a rendering issue, not a data or Firebase problem.

What React error #31 actually means (in your case)

“Objects are not valid as a React child”

This happens when something that is not a string/number/JSX is rendered inside JSX.

🔴 The real root cause

In HorizontalBarChart, this line is the killer:

<span className="h-bar-label" title={item.label}>{item.label}</span>


After adding Broker Allocation, at least one broker value is NOT a string
(it’s coming as an object or undefined) from Firestore / Excel.

So React tries to render:

<span>{ { name: "Broker X" } }</span> ❌


→ 💥 React error #31

✅ The correct fix (robust + future-proof)
1️⃣ Force broker labels to always be strings

Update your broker normalization helper like this:

const normalizeBrokerName = (raw?: any): string => {
  if (!raw) return 'Unassigned';

  // 🔒 HARD SAFETY: stringify objects
  if (typeof raw === 'object') {
    if ('name' in raw) return String(raw.name);
    return JSON.stringify(raw);
  }

  return String(raw).trim() || 'Unassigned';
};

2️⃣ Fix the DI Broker chart data (clean separation label vs %)

Replace your diBrokerData with this safe version:

const diBrokerData = useMemo(() => {
  const diBrokerIndex = buildUniqueDIBrokerIndex(filteredShipments);

  const groups: Record<string, { count: number; shipments: Shipment[] }> = {};

  diBrokerIndex.forEach((entry) => {
    const broker = normalizeBrokerName(entry.broker);
    if (!groups[broker]) groups[broker] = { count: 0, shipments: [] };
    groups[broker].count += 1; // UNIQUE DI
    groups[broker].shipments.push(...entry.shipments);
  });

  const total = Math.max(1, diBrokerIndex.size);

  return Object.entries(groups)
    .map(([broker, g]) => ({
      label: broker,                       // ✅ STRING ONLY
      value: g.count,                      // ✅ NUMBER ONLY
      percent: Math.round((g.count / total) * 100),
      shipments: g.shipments,
    }))
    .sort((a, b) => b.value - a.value);
}, [filteredShipments]);

3️⃣ Display the % inside the bar value, not the label

Update HorizontalBarChart rendering ONE LINE ONLY:

<span className="h-bar-value">
  {item.value} ({item.percent ?? Math.round((item.value / totalValue) * 100)}%)
</span>


✅ This avoids label pollution
✅ Keeps charts clickable
✅ No React crashes
✅ Looks executive-level clean

🧠 Why this fix is correct

✔ React must never receive objects inside text nodes
✔ Firestore + Excel often return objects silently
✔ This guarantees stability even if brokers come from:

Firestore refs

Excel merged cells

API responses later

